Here's a complete example. I'll use a weather API as a realistic REST wrapper.

---

### Tool Class — `WeatherTools.cs`

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    private static readonly JsonSerializerOptions JsonOptions = new() { WriteIndented = true };

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get current weather for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetCurrentWeather(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'London' or 'New York'")] string city,
        [Description("Units: 'metric' or 'imperial'")] string units = "metric",
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching weather for {City}", city);

        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/v1/weather?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&units={units}",
            cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

        var json = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
        using var doc = JsonDocument.Parse(json);
        return JsonSerializer.Serialize(doc, JsonOptions);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get 5-day weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name")] string city,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching forecast for {City}", city);

        var response = await httpClient.GetAsync(
            $"/v1/forecast?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}",
            cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();

        var json = await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
        using var doc = JsonDocument.Parse(json);
        return JsonSerializer.Serialize(doc, JsonOptions);
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

// Configure HttpClient with a base address for all tools that inject it
builder.Services.AddHttpClient<WeatherTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weatherservice.example.com");
    client.DefaultRequestHeaders.Add("Accept", "application/json");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();   // discovers all [McpServerToolType] classes

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

---

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK uses two injection styles:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|---------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services in constructor params — resolved once per tool invocation |
| **Method injection** | Static class | DI services as method params alongside user-facing params |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes DI services from tool parameters. Types registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, your own services) are **injected silently** — they never appear in the tool's JSON schema that the LLM sees. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

Built-in injectable types (no registration needed):
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — progress reporting
- `ILogger<T>` — logging (registered by default in Generic Host)

For `HttpClient`, register via `AddHttpClient<T>()` (typed client) or `AddHttpClient()` (general) in `Program.cs`. The SDK resolves it into your tool's constructor automatically.
